ChatGPT said:
Yes! You can create your own shortcuts (aliases) for commonly used Git commands ‚Äî like git a for git add ., git c for git commit -m, etc. These shortcuts work in any terminal, including the integrated terminals in VS Code, IntelliJ IDEA, or standalone terminal apps.

‚úÖ 1. Set Git Aliases (Recommended Approach)
üìå Example Aliases:
Alias	Full Git Command
git a	git add .
git c	git commit -m
git p	git push origin master
git s	git status
git co	git checkout
git b	git branch

üõ† How to Set Git Aliases
Run these commands once in your terminal:

bash
Copy
Edit
git config --global alias.a "add ."
git config --global alias.c "commit -m"
git config --global alias.p "push origin master"
git config --global alias.s "status"
git config --global alias.co "checkout"
git config --global alias.b "branch"
‚úÖ Usage:
bash
Copy
Edit
git a                  # git add .
git c "added login"    # git commit -m "added login"
git p                  # git push origin master
git s                  # git status
These aliases will now work in:

VS Code terminal

IntelliJ terminal

Any command line (PowerShell, Bash, Zsh, etc.)

üóÇÔ∏è 2. View or Edit Aliases in .gitconfig
To see or edit them manually:

bash
Copy
Edit
code ~/.gitconfig       # VS Code
You'll see something like:

ini
Copy
Edit
[alias]
    a = add .
    c = commit -m
    p = push origin master
    s = status
    co = checkout
    b = branch
‚ö†Ô∏è Gotchas
git c "message" expects the message immediately after, no prompt.

git commit -m alias can‚Äôt open the editor ‚Äî it's a fixed message shortcut.

If you're working on different branches, git p will always push to master ‚Äî so use it only when working on master.

Alternative for general push:

bash
Copy
Edit
git config --global alias.p "push"
üßë‚Äçüíª Bonus: Use Bash or Zsh Aliases (Optional)
If you want even shorter commands without typing git, add shell aliases.

Open your shell config file:
For Bash: code ~/.bashrc

For Zsh: code ~/.zshrc

For PowerShell: $PROFILE

Add:
bash
Copy
Edit
alias ga="git add ."
alias gc='git commit -m'
alias gp='git push origin master'
alias gs='git status'
Then run:

bash
Copy
Edit
source ~/.bashrc     # or ~/.zshrc
Now:

bash
Copy
Edit
ga                 # runs git add .
gc "fixed bug"     # git commit -m "fixed bug"
‚úÖ Best Practice Setup for Developers
bash
Copy
Edit
git config --global alias.a "add ."
git config --global alias.cm "commit -m"
git config --global alias.st "status"
git config --global alias.ps "push"
git config --global alias.plog "log --oneline --graph --all"
